Fig. 1
 shows the construction idea of the assessment indicator system. The study adopts SDG11 as the basic framework for assessment and combines the further requirements of the NUA for urban construction and evaluation needs. Moreover, based on existing studies, such as the mature international CPI evaluation (Wong, 2015), the standards on sustainable urban development developed by the ISO/TC 268 (Yang, 2019), and the UN-Habitat progress evaluation report for Goal 11 (United Nations Human Settlements Programme, 2018), this study reorganizes the targets of SDG11 and includes other relevant SDGs for appropriate extension and refinement. The field of basic quality of life is added, considering the function of cities as important gathering places for human beings and the principle of people-centered development. Considering that mitigation of the impact of urban disasters is usually achieved through urban planning and management, disaster reduction is merged into the field of urban planning and management. Ultimately, the evaluation system for sustainable UHS is divided into seven major fields: housing guarantee, sustainable transportation, human settlement management, heritage protection, basic quality of life, environmental protection, and livable public space (see Table 1
).

The UHS sustainability score is calculated in two steps (see Fig. 2
                        ). The first step is to calculate the indicator score by improved normalization after determining the indicator thresholds. The second step is to calculate the field scores from the indicator scores through equal weight aggregation, and then use the same method to obtain the UHS sustainability scores.



